{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58001c7b-63a0-4b0c-9db4-e54603cb647a","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` to avoid unbounded trace sizes.\n- `perf` is an alternative if you need OS-level/native frames, but requires `SYS_ADMIN` / `privileged` and kernel headers.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"737080a4-7426-4114-b95a-a3b2c1154602","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question - I can answer from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"7665:2FE433:D655F2:FB24F4:69FE8DD2"},"id":"0462e010-996b-4a29-9636-fae2782c6551","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:28:59.717Z","parentId":"7e118b62-d3b8-434f-9e88-9393f0cbcdef"}
